{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489401","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489401"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:15:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:15:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"649"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"649","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/649"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.79,0.02,0.04,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"649"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41756"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"649","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/649"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"649"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26692"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1282"},{"type":"tags","id":"1493"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3345"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3522"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10684"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10719"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44923"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41756","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/41756"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 22-year-old student attends the Emergency Department with right nasal obstruction and a progressively worsening headache with neck stiffness. His headache is generally absent when he wakes up, but gets worse as he gets up and during daily activities. It is mainly in the occipital region and there are no associated neurological features. The pain is of such severity, it is interfering with his studies. He describes a runny nose with discharge from both nostrils, with the right worse than left. This is especially worse in the mornings, where the nasal discharge \u0027pours\u0027 out of his right nostril as he leans forward to brush his teeth. He has a history of allergic rhinitis and family history of migraines. On further history he states that he was involved in a facial injury three weeks ago whilst playing soccer. He is afebrile. Anterior rhinosocopy shows a deviated septum to the left, thin clear nasal secretions bilaterally. Cranial nerve and neurological exam are normal. Palpation over his nose and maxillary sinuses are mildly tender bilaterally.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for his headache?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute sinusitis","Cerebrospinal fluid leak","Allergic rhinitis","Cluster headache","Early bacterial meningitis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Ecerebrospinal fluid leak\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA CSF leak can occur when there is disruption of the meninges, leading to an open communication between the subarachnoid space and other spaces. The most common aetiology is structural compromise due to craniofacial trauma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most common presentation of a patient with a cerebrospinal fluid leak is clear rhinorrhoea that may be accompanied by a headache, described as \u2018pressure-like\u2019 that may be positional in nature. This is supported by the patient in the stem, as the headache worsens throughout the day after changing position from supine to standing. Other supportive factors are the preceding event being traumatic, with a deviated nasal septum being evidence of this trauma. CSF leaks also present with clear rhinorrhoea, which is also present in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of CSF can be confirmed by testing the fluid for beta-2-transferrin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presentation of \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute sinusitis\u003C/strong\u003E can be divided into major and minor symptoms. Major symptoms include purulent nasal discharge, nasal congestion or obstruction, facial congestion, fullness, or pressure, or fever. Minor symptoms include headache, halitosis, and ear pain. The history of preceding trauma, clear rhinorrhoea, and lack of fever is more suggestive of a CSF leak due to a craniofacial fracture rather than acute sinusitis. This is reinforced by the fact the nasal discharge pours out when the patient leans forward, which is also more suggestive of a CSF leak.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBacterial meningitis\u003C/strong\u003E can be a complication of a CSF leak. However, this is unlikely in this patient, as there is an absence of photophobia, fever, or any petechial or purpuric rash. Despite the presence of headache and neck stiffness, the characteristics of the headache being worse throughout the day is not characteristic of meningitis.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis is unlikely to be a \u003Cstrong\u003Ecluster headache. \u003C/strong\u003ECluster headache presents as excruciating unilateral periorbital pain, not usually located in the occiput. They are typically chronic or episodic, and are unlikely to be precipitated by an acute traumatic event. Although ipsilateral cranial autonomic symptoms can present as rhinorrhoea typically other symptoms such as lacrimination, ptosis, conjunctival injection and eyelid edema can also be present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAllergic rhinitis\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely to be the cause of this man\u2019s symptoms. Typically, allergic rhinitis presents more with symptoms of sneezing, rhinorrhoea, watery eyes, and if chronic patients may also complain of postnasal drip, chronic nasal congestion, and obstruction. It can be intermittent, with particular triggers or exposures. This is not consistent with the history presented with the patient in the stem. \u00a0\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Nasal discharge after a head injury should always raise the possibility of a CSF leak."],"references":["Akhouri S. Allergic rhinitis [Internet]. StatPearls [Internet]. U.S. National Library of Medicine; 2021 [cited 2021Aug11]. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538186/","DeBoer DL. Acute sinusitis [Internet]. StatPearls [Internet]. U.S. National Library of Medicine; 2020 [cited 2021Aug11]. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK547701/","Runde TJ. Bacterial meningitis [Internet]. StatPearls [Internet]. U.S. National Library of Medicine; 2021 [cited 2021Aug11]. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470351/","Severson M. Cerebrospinal fluid leak [Internet]. StatPearls [Internet]. U.S. National Library of Medicine; 2020 [cited 2021Aug11]. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538157/","Lindemann, C. Cluster headache: A review of clinical presentation, evaluation, and management [Internet]. JAAPA 35(8):p 15-19, August 2022 [cited 2024Jan21] DOI: 10.1097/01.JAA.0000840484.33065.21"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26692"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"649"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26692","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/26692"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-01-23T08:41:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-01-23T08:41:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"649"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41756"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"35